# Authorization Code & Hybrid Flow Instructions

# Overview

This document is a manual that contains information on how to integrate your web application with the NBG Identity Servers using OpenId Connect Authorization Code Flow.

A web application consists of server-side code that reads, enhances and returns the index file, which then loads the client-side \- javascript \- code. Authorized HTTP requests to one or more **OAuth2** protected APIs must be supported.

Please check the [Identity Server Fundamentals](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1x26-1-p_vFWULDRE1LEbrqeGCpp8L0h4JK4QsoNowkM/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.xgm4o1mhk1aa) document for more information about the authorization code flow

# NBG Web Applications

Before we begin, let's break down an NBG web application. It consists of two separate parts: 

1. **client-side** code  
2. **server-side** code

The **client-side** code should have **no** perception or access to the authorization layer. All HTTP requests are unauthorized and target the reverse proxy \- or proxies \- that your server-side application has set up.

The **server-side** code creates a cookie where it stores all the user authentication/authorization related data (eg, the access token, user claims etc). Each time a request is received in the proxy source, the **Authorization** header is appended by reading the access token from the cookie (or from an application cache).

If all of your applicationâ€™s pages require authorization, then you only need to apply the **Authorize** attribute to your Index Controller (the one that reads the index.html file).

In case you have a public section, then the **Authorize** attribute cannot be used. You need to handle this in your client-side code by letting it know whether a user is currently logged in. You also need to provide a Controller. The recommended way is to create an **AuthController** with methods such as â€œIsLoggedIn, HasRole, Login, Logout etc. 

| âš ï¸Both the Login and Logout methods must be HTTP GÎ•Î¤ methods and the client-side code should navigate to them instead of performing an XHR request. This is because the authorization mechanism is based on redirects that must be handled by the userâ€™s web browser. |
| :---- |

# Configuration

First of all, fill in the form provided by the Identity Team (**ids.tech@nbg.gr**) to request a new Client. 

Then someone from the team will create the required configuration for your client and email you with the related information. You need to at least have a ClientId and a Secret for each of your environments.

## Configure Callback URLs {#configure-callback-urls}

A callback URL is a URL in your application that you would like the Authorization Server to redirect users to after they have authenticated. If not set, users will not be returned to your application after they log in. 

From version 8.1.0 and above, a callback URL with the suffix â€œ**/signin-nbg**â€ needs to be set for the client (for example: [https://localhost/myApp/**signin-nbg**](https://localhost/myApp/signin-nbg)). 

This change needs to be made in the Identity Administration application. If there is no access to the application, make a request to the IDENTITY SERVER-TECH team containing the URL to be added and the Client Id.

## Configure Logout URLs

A logout URL is a URL in your application that you would like the Authorization Server to redirect users to after they have logged out. If not set, users will not be able to log out from your application and will receive an error. 

From version 8.1.0 and above, a logout URL with the suffix â€œ**/signout-callback-nbg**â€ needs to be set for the client (for example: [https://localhost/myApp/**signout-callback-nbg**](https://localhost/myApp/signout-callback-nbg)). 

This change needs to be made in the Identity Administration application. If there is no access to the application, make a request to the IDENTITY SERVER-TECH team containing the URL to be added and the Client Id.

## Configure Required User Claims

User claims are user data your web application requires to operate. For example, if you wish to show the first name of the user who just logged in with a welcome message, you need the first\_name identity claim, which resides in the profile identity resource.

## Configure API Access

You have to declare which APIs you need to access from your application. Based on that information the related API scope(s) will be assigned to your client and thus the access token will be able to access the protected resource when you use it.

## Configure Automatic Access Token Management

## In case you need to add Automatic Access Token Management using a refresh token, have a look at this [section](#access-token-management-and-token-refresh).

# Authorization Code Flow



1. User initiates the login process  
2. Web App redirects the user to the [authorize endpoint](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gi9PLmxzTHIOmR4XqDFL9OTx6uQrc-Elm94mCxv7CaQ/edit#heading=h.yp47wrj4f9sa) providing details such as ClientId, Redirect URI, requested scopes, grant type, state etc  
3. Auth Server redirects the user to the login page.  
4. User enters their credentials.  
5. Auth Server validates user credentials.  
6. Auth Server redirects user back to the [specified Redirect url](#configure-callback-urls) providing a single-use auth code.  
7. Web App invokes the [token endpoint](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gi9PLmxzTHIOmR4XqDFL9OTx6uQrc-Elm94mCxv7CaQ/edit#heading=h.5xvm7wfb2bfs), providing the auth code and application credentials (ClientId, Client Secret, Redirect URI).  
8. Auth Server validates the auth code and application credentials.  
9. Auth Server responds with an ID token, access token and optionally, a refresh token.  
10. Web App sets the session cookie and loads the User Interface  
11. User clicks an action that requires an API call to load data  
12. Web App uses the access token to invoke an authorized Web API.  
13. Web API responds with requested data.

## Exchange Reference Token Flow

There are cases where you need the Authorization Server to issue an access token as a reference, but immediately after you need it to be in JWT format.

In these cases you may use the ***exchange\_reference\_token\_flow***. After you enable it in your client configuration the process to exchange the reference token for a JWT is as simple as invoking the [/connect/token](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gi9PLmxzTHIOmR4XqDFL9OTx6uQrc-Elm94mCxv7CaQ/edit#heading=h.5xvm7wfb2bfs) endpoint with the following parameters:

* **client\_id**: no explanation required.  
* **client\_secret**: no explanation required  
* **grant\_type**: set is value to: "exchange\_reference\_token"  
* **token**: value of the access token received after the authentication process is over. You can get this value by opening the authentication cookie and reading the claim â€œaccess\_tokenâ€  
* **scope**: the scopes to which you want the JWT access token to have access to. Use the values set in your configuration.

**Configuration**  
---

The method **AddNbgAuthCodeAuthentication** requires the following attributes to be passed as parameters, which are typically stored in the Authentication configuration section:

| {"Authentication": {    "Authority": "https://my.nbg.gr/identity",    "ClientId": "B683C610-A8AC-49E9-867A-C3F26314E900",    "ClientSecret": "\[redacted\]",    "Scopes": "openid sandbox-crowdfunding-public-api-v1"  }} |
| :---- |

Let's take a closer look at these attributes.

* **Authority**: This is the base URL of the authorization server you have selected. The available URLs are shown in the [IdS Authoriry URLs](#ids-authoriry-urls) section:  
* **ClientId**: No explanation required.  
* **ClientSecret**: No explanation required.  
* **Scopes**: Based on the user and api resources your client needs to access the fill in the responding value separated by the space character.

Providing the required properties is enough for using the package. If needed, you can override any other properties. For example:

| builder.AddNbgCodeFlowAuthentication(options \=\>{    options.SignedOutCallbackPath \= "/custom-signed-out";    options.SaveTokens \= true;    options.RequireHttpsMetadata \= false;    options.MapInboundClaims \= true;    options.NonceCookie.Name \= "CustomNonceCookie";    options.CorrelationCookie.Name \= "CustomCorrelationCookie";    options.TokenValidationParameters \= new Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens.TokenValidationParameters    {        ValidateIssuer \= true,        ValidIssuer \= "https://custom-issuer.example.com",        ValidateAudience \= true,        ValidAudience \= "custom-audience",        NameClaimType \= "custom-name-claim",        RoleClaimType \= "custom-role-claim"    };    options.Events \= new OpenIdConnectEvents    {        OnTicketReceived \= async context \=\>        {            // insert custom logic here        }    }}); |
| :---- |

The events you can override and insert your custom logic are: 

* **OnAuthenticationFailed**: Triggered when the authentication process fails. This event logs the error, resets the authentication workflow, and redirects the user to the application's root URL.  
* **OnRedirectToIdentityProvider**: Triggered before redirecting the user to the identity provider for authentication. It clears old nonce cookies (if enabled) and appends custom query parameters to the authorization request.  
* **OnRedirectToIdentityProviderForSignOut**: Triggered before redirecting the user to the identity provider for sign-out. Currently, this event does not perform any additional logic.  
* **OnAuthorizationCodeReceived**: Triggered when an authorization code is received from the identity provider. This event logs the received authorization code for debugging or tracking purposes.  
* **OnTicketReceived**: Triggered when the authentication ticket is received. This event is directly passed from the overrides without additional logic in this implementation.  
* **OnUserInformationReceived**: Triggered when user information is received from the identity provider. This event is also directly passed from the overrides without additional logic in this implementation.

### Utilities

#### Login

When the user presses the Login button:

1. The application triggers the Login action in the controller, which is decorated with the \[Authorize\] attribute.  
2. Since the user is not yet authenticated, the \[Authorize\] attribute redirects the user to the identity provider (configured in the NBG.NetCore.OpenId.AuthCodeClient package) for authentication.  
3. The identity provider presents a login page where the user enters their credentials.  
4. Upon successful authentication, the identity provider redirects the user back to the application using the callback URL (e.g., /signin-nbg).  
5. The application processes the authentication response, validates the tokens, and establishes a session using the configured cookie authentication scheme.  
6. The user is now logged in and can access protected resources or views.

#### Token Info & Claims

After successfully Login, the user is redirected to a page that contains information about the token and user claims.

This information can be retrieved as such:

Relevant file: UserInfo.cs

| var claims \= User.Claims;var accessToken \= await Context.GetTokenAsync(OpenIdConnectParameterNames.AccessToken);var idToken \= await Context.GetTokenAsync(OpenIdConnectParameterNames.IdToken);var tokenType \= await Context.GetTokenAsync(OpenIdConnectParameterNames.TokenType);var refreshToken \= await Context.GetTokenAsync(OpenIdConnectParameterNames.RefreshToken); |
| :---- |

Note: Context refers to the standard HttpContext property available inside an MVC Controller or a Razor page.

#### Logout

When the user presses the Logout button:

1. The application triggers the LogOut action in the controller.  
2. The LogOut action calls the SignOut method, which:  
* Ends the user's session by clearing the authentication cookies.  
* Redirects the user to the identity provider to log out from the identity server (via the NbgOpenIdConnectDefaults.AuthenticationScheme).  
3. After the logout process is complete, the identity provider redirects the user back to the application using the RedirectUri specified in the SignOut method (e.g., the SignedOut action).  
4. The SignedOut action renders a confirmation page (e.g., "You have been signed out.") to inform the user that they have successfully logged out. Alternatively, you can redirect to the application root.

#### Access Token Management and Token Refresh {#access-token-management-and-token-refresh}

In file Program.cs, the line:

| builder.Services.AddOpenIdConnectAccessTokenManagement(); |
| :---- |

configures the app to use the Duende.AccessTokenManagement package for managing access tokens and enabling token refresh functionality. This is an optional feature and you can choose whether you want your application to use it or not.

**Access Token Management**  
Access token management refers to the process of securely handling access tokens, which are short-lived credentials used to authenticate API requests. These tokens are typically issued by an identity provider (e.g., OpenID Connect) during the authentication process. Proper management ensures that tokens are stored securely, used efficiently, and refreshed when they expire.

**Token Refresh**  
Access tokens have a limited lifespan for security reasons. When an access token expires, the application can use a refresh token (a long-lived credential issued alongside the access token) to request a new access token without requiring the user to log in again. This process is known as token refresh.

**Prerequisites**  
In order for the above functionality to work, you also need to allow Offline Access in the Identity Administration application, in the Advanced tab of your client. If there is no access to the application, contact the IDENTITY SERVER-TECH team requesting to allow Offline Access for your Client Id.![][image1]

**How does AddOpenIdConnectAccessTokenManagement help?**  
The AddOpenIdConnectAccessTokenManagement method:  
1\.	Enables Automatic Token Refresh: It configures the app to automatically refresh access tokens using the refresh token before they expire, ensuring uninterrupted API access.  
2\.	Simplifies Token Handling: It abstracts the complexity of managing token lifecycles, allowing developers to focus on application logic.  
3\.	Integrates with OpenID Connect: It works seamlessly with OpenID Connect authentication flows, making it ideal for apps that rely on secure API communication.  
By including this line, the app is equipped to handle token expiration gracefully, improving both security and user experience. Developers building on this sample can rely on this functionality to ensure their applications maintain secure and reliable API access.

**How to remove Access Token Management and Token Refresh?**  
If there is no need for these features, you can delete this line in Program.cs:

| builder.Services.AddOpenIdConnectAccessTokenManagement(); |
| :---- |

You should also remove this line in the file Nbg.AuthCode.SampleWebClient.csproj:

| \<PackageReference Include="Duende.AccessTokenManagement.OpenIdConnect" Version="3.2.0" /\> |
| :---- |

# Troubleshooting

If your application is not functioning as expected when using the package, follow these steps to diagnose and resolve the issue:

1. Configuration

Verify that your configuration values (e.g., Authority, ClientId, ClientSecret, Scopes) are correctly set in your applicationâ€™s configuration.

2. Check Application Logs

Review your application's logs for any errors or warnings related to authentication. Ensure that logging is properly configured to capture detailed information about the authentication process. The package relies on the application's DI container to provide the logger.

3. Verify Authentication Cookie

Confirm that the authentication cookie has been created successfully. The cookie name is set to NbgOpenIdConnectDefaults.DefaultCookieName by default. You can inspect cookies using browser developer tools or by enabling middleware to log cookie-related information.

4. Investigate Claims Issues

If the authentication cookie exists, check if the expected claims are present. Missing or incorrectly mapped claims can cause issues.

5. Test in Multiple Environments

In case you have only tested your application in the QA environment, ensure you also test it locally or in the DEV environment. The QA environment has infrastructure differences, such as a Load Balancer, which could affect the behavior of your application. Testing in multiple environments helps isolate whether the issue is related to your application or the infrastructure.

6. Infinite Redirects Issue

If your application encounters an infinite redirects issue during the OpenID Connect authentication flow, it may be caused by improper token management. To resolve this, you can try using the Duende.AccessTokenManagement.OpenIdConnect package, which provides automatic access token lifetime management. Refer to [this section](#access-token-management-and-token-refresh) for more.
